    <item id="import-auto-id1350386">In equation form, the general relationship between voltage and electric field is
      <equation id="eip-894"><m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>E</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">–</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:mrow><m:mn>Δ</m:mn><m:mi fontstyle="italic">V</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>Δ</m:mn><m:mi fontstyle="italic">s</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mfrac></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mo>,</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow></m:math></equation>

where <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>Δ</m:mn><m:mi fontstyle="italic">s</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> is the distance over which the change in potential, <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>Δ</m:mn><m:mi/><m:mi>V</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math>, takes place. The minus sign tells us that <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext mathvariant="bold">E</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> points in the direction of decreasing potential.) The electric field is said to be the <emphasis effect="italics">gradient</emphasis> (as in grade or slope) of the electric potential. </item>
